description:
secretx-core/src/lib.rs:1022-1059: percent_decode uses 'let bytes = s.as_bytes(); let mut i = 0; while i < bytes.len() { ... i += 1 / i += 3 ... }' which is straight-out-of-K&R-style imperative byte processing.

A more idiomatic shape walks an iterator of bytes:

    let mut iter = s.bytes();
    let mut out = Vec::with_capacity(s.len());
    while let Some(b) = iter.next() {
        if b == b'%' {
            let hi = iter.next().and_then(hex_digit).ok_or_else(...)?;
            let lo = iter.next().and_then(hex_digit).ok_or_else(...)?;
            out.push((hi << 4) | lo);
        } else {
            out.push(b);
        }
    }

This eliminates the i+1/i+2 indexing (which is correct here but a class of bug elsewhere) and makes the 'consume up to 3 bytes per iteration' shape obvious from the structure.

The error message 'at position {i}' would need to be tracked separately — fine, that's what enumerate() gives you.

P3 because the existing code is correct, well-tested, and short. The rewrite is purely a clarity improvement.
